0:Once I was hit with the cold air of the outside world, my headache ever so slightly subsided.\p;
100:The city had a more restless atmosphere to it than usual, probably due to the earthquake from earlier. I didn't know that for sure, though.\p;
200:In the distance, the sound of sirens continued to echo endlessly, but I wasn't sure if they were from ambulances or fire trucks. Could've been both.\p;
300:Yamate-dori, which was one block away from me, was completely jammed up. Traffic was bumper-to-bumper.\p;
400:There were multiple visible accidents—most head-on—and the cars involved had simply been left abandoned on the road, their drivers nowhere to be found.\p;
500:Those abandoned cars were the cause of this traffic jam. The other drivers were honking their horns like crazy.\p;
600:As I was wandering the streets to get to school, I saw a dog crossing the road, barking.\p;
700:It was a chihuahua sprinting at full speed, dragging its leash behind its small body.\p;
800:Its eyes were bloodshot, and a large amount of drool was dripping from its open mouth.\n;It had probably gotten separated from its owner.\p;
900:As I absentmindedly watched it get farther and farther away, I tripped on something and nearly fell over.\p;
1000:The asphalt was cracked, and one section of the road was ever so slightly lower than the rest.\p;
1100:It had most likely come from the earthquake.\p;
1200:Stopping right there, I looked up at the sky.\p;
1300:There were a few white clouds drifting calmly across the dull light blue.\p;
1400:Just after the earthquake'd hit, something similar to an aurora had formed in the sky and tainted it pure white, but the traces of it had already disappeared.\p;
